Extending from the south-east angle of the main group of buildings are the walls and foundations of a secondary group of buildings (17, 18). These have been identified as the hospitium or the abbot's house, but they occupy the position in which the infirmary is more usually found. The hall was a very spacious apartment, measuring 83&amp;nbsp;ft. in length by 48&amp;nbsp;ft. 9&amp;nbsp;inches in breadth, which was divided by two rows of columns. The fish-ponds lay between the monastery and the river to the south. The abbey mill was situated about 80 yards to the north-west. The millpool may be distinctly traced, together with the [[goit]] or mill stream.{{sfn|Venables|1911}}

== Dissolution and later history ==
[[File:Thomas Girtin 003.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Kirkstall Abbey, by [[Thomas Girtin]]]]
On 22 November 1539 the abbey was surrendered to [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]'s commissioners in the Dissolution of the monasteries.&lt;ref name=&quot;Dis&quot;&gt;{{Citation |title=Kirkstall History Dissolution|url=http://cistercians.shef.ac.uk/kirkstall/history/dissolution/| publisher=shef.ac.uk |accessdate=15 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; It was awarded to [[Thomas Cranmer]] in 1542, but reverted to the crown when Cranmer was executed in 1556.  Sir Robert Savile purchased the estate in 1584, and it remained in his family's hands for almost a hundred years.  In 1671 it passed into the hands of the Brudenell family, the [[Earl of Cardigan|Earls of Cardigan]]. Much of the stone was removed for re-use in other buildings in the area, including the steps leading to [[Leeds Bridge]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=Leeds nostalgia: Leeds Bridge |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/your-leeds/nostalgia/leeds-nostalgia-leeds-bridge-1-7215683 |accessdate=30 September 2018 |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=20 April 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt;

During the 18th century the picturesque ruins attracted artists of the [[Romanticism|Romantic movement]] and were painted by artists including [[J. M. W. Turner]], [[John Sell Cotman]] and [[Thomas Girtin]].&lt;ref name=&quot;YAS&quot;&gt;{{Citation |title=Celebrating 850 years of Kirkstall Abbey|url=http://www.medieval.yas.org.uk/content/kirkstall.html| publisher=Yorkshire Archaeological Society|accessdate=15 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1889 the abbey was sold to [[John Thomas North|Colonel John North]], who presented it to [[Leeds City Council]]. The Council undertook a major restoration project and the abbey was opened to the public in 1895.&lt;ref name=&quot;IoE&quot;&gt;{{NHLE |num=1256668 |desc=Kirkstall Abbey |accessdate=15 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The [[African Americans|African American]] novelist [[William Wells Brown]] visited Kirkstall Abbey in 1851, writing about his experience.&lt;ref name=&quot;:1&quot;&gt;{{Cite web|last=Williams|first=Joe|date=27 October 2020|title=Nature Prevails at Kirkstall Abbey|url=https://museumsandgalleries.leeds.gov.uk/featured/nature-kirkstall-abbey/|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 October 2020|website=Leeds Museums and Galleries}}&lt;/ref&gt; Using poetry and poetic language, he described the 'pensive beauty' of the desolate ruins in their 'pastoral luxuriance' showing his appreciation of British literature as well as an interest in nature and local history.&lt;ref name=&quot;:1&quot; /&gt;

== The abbey today ==
[[File:Kirkstall Abbey Kapitelsaal.jpg|thumb|left|[[Chapter house|Chapter House]] of the abbey]]
[[File:Kirkstall Abbey Kirche von Westen.jpg|thumb|right|Western Elevation of the abbey]]
The abbey is a Grade I [[listed building]] and [[Scheduled Monument|Scheduled Ancient Monument]].&lt;ref name=&quot;IoE&quot;/&gt; After a £5.5&amp;nbsp;million renovation programme there is a new visitor centre with interactive exhibits which illustrates the history of the abbey and the lives of the monks.  Entry to the Abbey itself is via the visitor centre – free of charge, but with a donation box. Occasionally, guided tours are available (free of charge).

The ''Leeds Shakespeare Festival'', performed by the [[British Shakespeare Company]], took place annually in the cloisters from 1995 until 2009. The abbey grounds are a public park, and are used for occasional events such as the annual Kirkstall Festival and the Kirkstall Fantasia open-air concerts.

On the other side of the main road, the Grade II* listed former abbey gatehouse now forms the [[Abbey House Museum]].
